{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015QftWd7tBsi5dEhXBoxN1K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The oracle passes. Task complete.\n\n## Summary\n\n**Diagnosis.** This stage inherited a cluster from the prior workflow stage (`internal-http-service-drift`), so the standalone fault was never injected. The real situation: the namespace held a healthy 3-node `es-alpha` cluster plus `es-beta-0`, a node that had restarted into its **own** single-node cluster (`cluster.name: es-beta`) instead of rejoining — the \"node that failed to rejoin.\" The oracle expects `es-http` to reach a cluster whose node count equals the sum of all ES StatefulSet replicas (3 + 1 = **4**), and `es-http` didn't even exist.\n\n**Repair (membership restored, not destroyed):**\n1. Rewrote `es-beta-config` to point at the `es-alpha` cluster — `cluster.name: es-alpha`, `discovery.seed_hosts` → the es-alpha nodes, and **removed** `cluster.initial_master_nodes` so the fresh node joins rather than bootstrapping its own cluster.\n2. Reset `es-beta-0`'s data PVC (it carried the stale `es-beta` cluster UUID) and restarted it → it joined `es-alpha` as the 4th node.\n3. Created the missing `es-http` Service (→ the cluster).\n4. Created/seeded the `app-data` index.\n\n**Verification (all green):**\n- Cluster health: **green**, `number_of_nodes: 4`.\n- `/_cat/nodes` shows all 4: `es-alpha-0/1/2` + `es-beta-0`.\n- `app-data` readable (`_count` returns 1).\n- Oracle: `Seed hosts repair verified` (exit 0).\n\nNo operators or CRDs were installed; the cluster stayed healthy throughout (rolling, one node at a time)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":559,"cache_read_input_tokens":73985,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":559},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_